    "recap_headline": "University of Oklahoma Athletics",
    "recap_text": "NORMAN\n\u2014 No. 9 Oklahoma took the SEC opening weekend series over No. 22 Texas A&M with a 12-11 win on a windy Sunday afternoon at Kimrey Family Stadium.\nThe Sooners (17-3, 2-1) scored in six of eight trips to the plate, putting up two-plus runs in four innings. After serving a one-game suspension on Saturday, junior\nJaxon Willits\npaced the team with four runs batted in on Sunday in a 2-for-4 performance with a double.\nOklahoma jumped out to a 6-0 lead through two innings before Texas A&M (16-3, 1-2) rallied to eventually tie the game in the eighth on a three-run double. OU responded in the home half of the eighth, scoring the go-ahead run on a bases-loaded walk drawn by\nCamden Johnson\n.\nJohnson led OU at the plate with a 3-for-4 day and three RBIs, while Willits had a team-high four RBIs and finished the weekend 5-for-7 with seven runs batted in. Senior\nTrey Gambill\nhit his fourth home run of the season on a two-run shot in the third inning, finishing 2-for-4 with three RBIs.\nOU starting LHP\nCord Rager\nwent three innings and struck out six while allowing four runs on five hits and one walk. Junior\nJason Bodin\nearned his second win in relief on the weekend, hurling the final two innings and striking out one while allowing two runs on two hits. Senior\nJackson Cleveland\nwent 3.1 innings and struck out a season-high four.\nPitchers of Record\nWin:\nJason Bodin\n(3-0)\nLoss: Grant Cunningham (0-1)\nStatistical Snapshot\nCamden Johnson\n| 3-for-4, 1 2B, 3 RBI\nJaxon Willits\n| 2-for-4, 1 2B, 4 RBI\nTrey Gambill\n| 2-for-4, 1 HR, 3 RBI\nCord Rager\n| 3.0 IP, 5 H, 4 R, 4 ER, 1 BB, 6 K\nJason Bodin\n| 2.0 IP, 2 H, 2 R, 2 ER, 0 BB, 1 K\nNotes\nOU improved to 17-3 on the season and 13-3 at Kimrey Family Stadium.\nThe Sooners are 2-1 in SEC play with the win and 1-0 in conference series. It marks the second straight season OU has opened conference play with a series win.\nIt was OU's fourth win over Texas A&M in the last five games vs. the Aggies and first conference win over A&M since beating them in a Big 12 series in 2010.\nOU moved to 3-1 in ranked matchups on the season.\nThe win was OU's fourth victory by one run this season. OU is 4-0 in one-run games.\nOU continued its streak of an extra-base hit in every game of the season with three on the day.\nThe Sooner pitching staff struck out 12 batters on the day, the 14th game of 20 this season that the staff has struck out 10-plus.\nTrey Gambill\nhit his fourth home run of the season, matching his season total from 2025.\nJackson Cleveland\nstruck out a season-high four and went a season-long 3.1 innings.\nUp Next\nOU plays its first true road game Tuesday in Hammond, La., meeting Southeastern Louisiana at 6 p.m. CT. Following the midweek matchup, OU will swing down to Baton Rouge for its second weekend of conference play, March 19-21, vs. the reigning national champs and 13th-ranked LSU.\nThe series at Alex Box Stadium will be OU's first trip to LSU since a Super Regional matchup in 2013 that saw the Tigers beat the Sooners to advance to Omaha.\nSeason and single game tickets for the 2026 season are available now on\nSoonerSports.com/tickets\n. For more information about Oklahoma baseball tickets, contact the OU Athletics Ticket Office at 405-325-2424, by email at\noutickets@ou.edu\nor by visiting\nSoonerSports.com/tickets\n.\nFor updates and more information on Oklahoma baseball, follow the Sooners on X and Instagram (\n@OU_Baseball\n) and like\nOklahoma Baseball\non Facebook."
